@ 17 ditto 1681
Leuven Andreas verrou
in answer to yd of 6: curitt as to serve you in comission for yd mony att
Dunquerque, that is that you shall order yd mony there to be payd to mee or
order which then Ill draw from theme, remit for london, & from thenme
to what place in grland you will & to whom you will catas short a tne
as itt shall be to be had, & then shall give you an accompt of the ex. from
one place to the other, as itt shall prove demanding onely for my pamis
one Pc. for wee have no bills here directely for Irland, butt haveing
remitted yd mony to london to my correspondents there, they will remitt itt
for mee to yd order & otherwise itt is not to be don which is the nadfull
att present from
@ 11 ditto 1681
Amsterdam De Hulter & van Homright
Msss. op 8 deser was aen ul mijnen leesten, waer aen mij referrere ondertusschen
wegens de 20 vaten boter niet vernomen, de cleyn fristasie wort minder gearnt
omdes will de refacie & terra teweel is op de selve, eghter geen hebbende en kan
geen verkoopen, een weijnngh tot assortement, soude my inde kennisse
onderhouden soo de verse nievere komt te arriveren soude daer van wel pertije
tegens den winter konnen debiteren agoverno wat de gementioneerde
wolle belanght, mijnen wercknun thuys gekomen sijnde heeft de selve
niet wel bevonden, ende mij geheelyk ontraden, oversulx wenste wel noch
pertije te hebben gelijk de 5 leste balen door ul voor mij gekoght, want
die wel bevallen, ofte een stercke proma segouische soorte van ons 31 sp
niet suprafijne maer, een stercke bequane soorte tot coleure lakens te
maken, oversulx gelieft mij devrintscas te doen, te doen informeeren
ofte eenige soorte danighe is te bekomen, ende vande selve staelen ofte mons.
aen mij te senden om vervolgens te ordonneeren den inkoop de pertije
voor Amr. Roosendael afgeladen is verkoght, want anders bijde reste sonde
geen pr. segruische sterke sor te konnende vinden
hebbe bekomen anaer
laet stalen besorgen diransoria segoiiene ofte van bijde soo mogelijk is

London Abram vivian
Sr. mj last to you was on the 10 curitt to which referre you sence recd. yd of 29 past
with invoyce for the bale N.37: with 32 bayes which wilst came to late to come
by smith must exspect them by pindar as also the other bayes & what Elle is
remaining to compleat the full orders intrim I hope still to see you here, when
wee will fully discours off all this day is sent to newport the packett N. 19 cour
boath to thether 11 p. laces according to the inclosed invoyce, because the least
is for Cruwat laces acor, so could not well make itt one packett, butt itt is
in 2 which boath are tyed up to ghether that when they come att Dovers they
can besent forward distinetels the biggest is marckett with doth coud
N. 206„ 207 „ 209„ 211„ 213 „ 214 d& the other the rest I wish them safe to yd haid
& doubt not butt they will give good content N. 206 is the reece you sent
mee to be made 5 yd & is long now a 6 & I payd a 5¼ att ƒ11:4 where
in I can fuithen serve you or any other freind freely command mee whist I ave
London Henry Maynard

@ 12 ditto
S. my last to you was on the 6: curitt sence recd yd of 29 pass, as yett wee have no
news of sjmons, god send him well, I wonder what is become of him: I have made
you deb in my acctt. for the £109:6 t you receaved of m. Hawen & I do
write this day, because I am iust going for Brussels where I hope to finde good
store of mony, that I might be in a condition to send you a good supply p. next
post on boath acctt. on which you may depend I have given you creditt for my half
share in the bale of redds, aboard warner: I perceave that I did not well eapress
mij self as for the northren trade: I shall onely answer, that when you shall
be here, I shall shew you how I am served by others, and in case I can bj yd meanes
have the same sorts & goods, shall wholly keep to you, for you may be confident
Ilove rather to have to do with one all alone then severall, where fore what
I can not well explaine by letters, shall shew you by the deed & shall endeavour
to bring itt so farr, that wee might have agenerall trade toghether, & when you
see the goods the one bij the other you will better be able to iudge what measirres
that to taker then I can make you understood, for mr. freemans buying
was not well, in hills I confess is better, and I beleave when I see you, shall, accquaid
you yett of abetter & the best wee want, to bring our whare house in reputation
which I endeavour to procure as well as proffitt intrim returne you thanckes
that you preferre mee before others, you may assure yd self I shall do all
I can to please you & to promote yd intrest as well as mine, & to mte
all things the more I have a small trade from Exon, in which in case you be
accquainted, shall be willing to proceed as in the rest for what I can have with
one letter, shall not inclina to trouble others you have given a letter
shall not incoie of creditt to yd freind mr. Henry furnace, which comes up
on the lace trade where in Ibeginne to bes much accquancted, so you
maij be sure I shall do for him as much as if yd selfs was here, and endeavour
to give him good content, whilst I hope this will give you satis faction till
Isee you & so remaine
